## Core features (currently live)

### 1. Live workout tracker
The heart of the app. Users can start a live workout session with a built-in timer and add exercises as they go, crossing them off as they complete them. This makes Royal useful in the gym in real time — not just as a post-workout logging tool.

The design principle here mirrors Strava's: one tap to start, as much or as little detail as the user wants to add. A user can log "went to the gym" in seconds, or build out a full session with every exercise, set, and rep tracked in detail.

### 2. Wellness logging
Beyond workouts, users can log the full picture of their wellness life:
- **Nutrition** — meals, dietary choices
- **Wellness activities** — recovery, sleep, mindfulness, sauna, red light therapy, skincare, supplements, and other lifestyle products and routines

Logging should always feel frictionless. One tap for simple entries, depth available for those who want it.

### 3. Activity feed
Logged activities surface to a shared social feed. Posts can include photos, text, and product tags. Feed is filterable by category: All, Workouts, Meals, Wellness.

This is where Royal becomes social — not a broadcasting platform, but a genuine community of people sharing how they actually live.

### 4. Catalog
Each user has a personal catalog — a grid view of products, supplements, and services they actually use, with optional referral links or codes attached. This is the royalties layer.

Users can:
- Add products to their catalog permanently
- Periodically post catalog items to the feed to promote recommendations to followers
- Attach referral codes or links so followers can purchase through them

When a follower uses a referral link, the catalog owner earns a commission — framed within Royal as earning royalties. The language matters: this is not affiliate marketing, it is earning royalties on your lifestyle recommendations.

### 5. Social graph
Users can follow others, view their activity, and discover people through the feed. Profiles show logged activity history and the user's catalog.

### 6. Smart suggestions
The app surfaces contextual nudges based on activity — for example, suggesting a recovery session after 5+ workouts in a week.

